<TITLE> France says to host informal Lebanon meeting </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, June 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - France said on Friday it would invite Lebanese political leaders and prominent members of civil society to an informal meeting aimed at improving political dialogue in the country. "The minister has ... taken the initiative to invite to France representatives of all the Lebanese political forces and of civil society to participate in an informal meeting to help restore a dialogue between all political forces of the country," a French foreign ministry spokesman said. Spokesman Denis Simonneau also told a news conference the meeting was likely to be held in late June. Lebanon was plunged into its worst political crisis since the 1975-1990 civil war when opposition ministers quit the cabinet of Prime Minister Fouad Siniora last November after the ruling majority refused opposition demands for veto power. The majority accused the opposition, made up mainly of Christian and pro-Syrian Shi'ite Muslim factions, of trying to block passage of an international tribunal to try suspects in the 2005 killing of ex-premier Rafik al-Hariri. Pro-government leaders say Syria was behind Hariri's assassination. Damascus denies any hand in it. France's Simoneau said the aim of the planned meeting was "to help the Lebanese meet amongst themselves in a convivial, passion-free setting which we hope will enable the renewal of this dialogue between the different parties". "On the date, the end of this month is being discussed but the dates have not yet been totally established. On the location, it's a location we wish to keep discreet," he sa
